.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3236573043BFFFCFF2FFF47FF1671EA" pageId="9" pageNumber="330" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8636F8043BFFFCFF2FFF47FF1671EA" blockId="9.[151,1437,150,392]" pageId="9" pageNumber="330">
<emphasis id="B94DEAEA043BFFFCFF2FFF47FE8371C6" bold="true" box="[199,328,186,212]" pageId="9" pageNumber="330">Etymology</emphasis>
. From the Latin 
<taxonomicName id="4C394D7B043BFFFCFDE0FF46FD9571C6" authorityName="Hansson" authorityYear="2022" box="[520,606,187,212]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Diglyphomorphomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="330" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis id="B94DEAEA043BFFFCFDE0FF46FD9571C6" box="[520,606,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="330">cristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
= ridged, referring to the ridge (carina) along anterior margin of pronotal collar.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
